ful, creativity. The book begins with a critique of the neo-Kantian tradition in legal theory (Hart, Dworkin, and Habermas) and proceeds to draw on Bergson's theory of perception and memory and Spinoza's conception of ethics in order to frame creativity as a necessary feature of judgment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Phenomenology.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362724640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503627246423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503627246/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles